description._content: Ever since I spotted my first graffiti while driving in the Southside of the city, I have always been on the lookout for more. Somebody once told me that, once you start appreciating paint, it's hard to stop. And it's proven to be true. My thing with graffiti is, I don't really understand what a lot of it says with their cryptic style of writing. What I see is the beauty and the artistry that is on that wall. My apologies to the artists as most of the time, I couldn't even figure out their signatures, but I really appreciate the work (I know the one up there is C3PO). This particular wall is actually in the Northside. And that is the Blue Line tracks in the back.

description._content: Does all street art brighten a community? Find the answer and voice your opinion at www.spudart.org/blogs/randomthoughts_comments/5461_0_3_0_C/

The string was strung along the seats. I'm not really sure what the function of the lines were, because there were photos hanging by the lines. And the photos didn't have a visual or conceptual connection to the lines. 

I got the feeling that they first hung up the photos, and then it didn't seem that exciting enough, so they added the string. 

Ok, so that was a rather, uh, not as positive view on this installation. But I did like the string. There was a certain energy to the lines. It was like laser beams. They were like action lines in a cartoon, implying a motion. 

The photos were mostly of architecture. I wish I got more shots of the photographs. The architecture was mostly stable strong architecture. The photos were really nice. It makes me wonder how the action dynamic lines work with the architecture.
Illinois. It has corn. This train. It has corn.
It was fun standing behind these hanging strands.

This part of the train was one of the most ignored, but one of the most interested cars. People would look and think they saw nothing. Just potato sacks. 

But those potato sacks did multiple things. 

One: They created a funky environment. Omnious. Stark. Creepy. 

Two: Standing in the middle of the potato sacks, you can breath in the burlap. It was a weird sensation to breath in burlap. 

Three: Filter view onto the seats. I'm not sure if this third function was intentional. But it was interesting viewing the seats through the translucency of the burlap. It was almost like there were ghosts sitting in the seats behind the burlap. 

Four: Softening. This kinda goes with the first one where the environment gets transformed. But there was something about the softness of the hanging burlap.

photo.title: Art on Track: Bombs that go bloom

description._content:
I last saw this artwork in the Chicago Cultural Center in June 2011. "Bombs That Go Bloom" by Stuart G. Hall. And now it's very interesting to see it in a completely different context on a CTA train. The way the missiles swayed with the train added a great kinetic feeling to this work. Plus the changing urban background provided a great backdrop that put this work into a real-life context. As if these missles could be dropped anywhere, including downtown Chicago. 

I got a minute-long video of this piece with the swaying and changing background. I'll post it to youtube.

My chalk art "Jesus Plays Chess" on Michigan Avenue in Chicago. I'm studying the ways that Jesus figured things out. I'm using chess pieces as a metaphor. Thank you to Cheryl Williams for organizing the Friday event. I came back on Sunday and worked more, see photos at www.selflearners.net/art/?e=20110710JesusPlaysChess Then the rain obliterated it! Here are explanations: * a knocked down king as the "stumbling block" that Jesus didn't want us or him to be * a pawn, small like a child, that can walk through the narrow gate of life and get promoted as a queen (Jesus), attracted to the living Jesus of the Sermon on the Mount, the Kingdom of Heaven, the culture I seek * the chess box, the wide gate of destruction, into which pieces go down into, yet can be miraculously pulled out of, for example, when a queen is needed because a pawn was promoted, the path for those attracted to the dead and risen Jesus of the cross * a donkey that goes round in circles, turning a millstone, like the scientific method, the slowest way of learning * a pawn in front of a queen, which is to say, if you accept one of the little ones, then you accept Jesus * four squares that are four ways of distinguishing the truths of the heart and the world, the four positive commandments * six hops across pairs of those squares, across the gap between the bad that creeps up and the ways we fix our bad relationships, the negative commandments "thou shalt not..." or "you have heard it said... but I say to you..." * a Pegasus knight released from one hand of God the Father (the king) and headed towards another hand

The most poignant of all the "Rememeber me" magnets so far came with this white bicycle for Alicia Frantz (view the entire Remember me series at www.spudart.org/series/remember-me). Locked up under the Metra overpass, this bicycle is a memorial for the woman who "heard everyday sounds as music." The bike is decorated with shiny irish beads and white pearls turned all smoky from the constant passing cars entering and leaving the I-90/94 Kennedy Expressway. The walkway is elevated up a few feet making it eye level with all the cars that pass by. As I was photographing this bicycle, I thought of all the cars for the past five years that pass by this bicycle every day as part of their morning commute. I wonder how forgotten this bicycle has gotten to those who are used to seeing it. As a fellow bicyclist, it makes me pause and consider the life of someone who died on their bike, probably by a car zooming onto or off the expressway. Maybe Alicia Frantz be remembered.

photo.title: Have a ball today on the Michigan Avenue bridge

description._content: Seven balls happily sit on the relief of the northeast bridge tower in downtown Chicago. It was quite an experience photographing these seven balls. Normally when I place artwork downtown, it's a single small piece and nobody pays attention. In fact, most people just pass it by without noticing. But as I was photographing these seven bouncy balls, all these tourists were coming up looking at them. One boy even asked me if I placed them there. I happily explained, "yes, i did. And when I'm done photographing them, I leave them there for people to take." He said it was cool. They got such attention that as soon as I walked away people were walking up to them reading them and some took some. I shot some video of people's reactions. But then I think people felt awkward cuz there was this dude standing in the distance with a tripod in hand and a camera pointing at them for more then just a couple seconds. I moved over to the gate and placed my camera on top of the bridge gate box and simply let my camera record. I still have to go back and edit that video, as I wasn't watching people. I wanted them to feel natural to approach the artwork and take it. As I was letting my camera record video, I pulled out my cell phone to make it look normal that I was just standing there hanging out. So what do I pull up on my iPhone? My favorite time-filler of the past couple months, Instagram. As I'm looking through the Instagram feed, I saw that lokate posted a photo of bouncy balls! With a message to me! Yaaaay! What a great surprise! instagr.am/p/GhYUW/ And all while I was videotaping people picking up bouncy balls! I was so happy to see the photo, I was bouncing up and down like a bouncy ball. :-) ----------- ABOUT THE BOUNCY BALLS "Have a ball today" reads on one side of the signs. "Pass it along" reads on the flip side of each sign. This is the first time I used the phrase "Pass it along" on the backside of the bouncy ball signs. As I was writing out the little signs with "Have a ball today" I was thinking of putting an email address on the back of the sign for people to email me, if they wish. And then thinking about that sort of interactivity, what I really want with this project is for people to share the bouncy balls. Just as I shared these with the finder, I would love for the finder to share it with others. This project is about finding something fun. And having fun with it. I absolutely love bouncy balls. They are fun to just bounce around while walking. Or to bounce in the elevator. Brainstorm for this project: www.spudart.org/blogs/randomthoughts_comments/5186_0_3_0_C/ Bouncy balls on the train: www.spudart.org/blogs/randomthoughts_comments/1232_0_3_0_C/ Bouncy balls on escalators: www.spudart.org/blogs/randomthoughts_comments/3724_0_3_0_C/ Bouncy balls elevator challenge (WEBCOMIC): www.spudart.org/blogs/randomthoughts_comments/4322_0_3_0_C/ Bouncy balls left in public (PHOTOS): www.flickr.com/photos/spudart/sets/72157624365405148 Bouncy balls left in public (VIDESO): www.youtube.com/watch?v=1A0UWMYx2xg&p=15D4C44DD01A90AE ----------- ABOUT THE SCULPTURE The sculpture that these bouncy balls are sitting on is a relief by James Earle Fraser named "Discoverers." . . . . From chicago-outdoor-sculptures.blogspot.com/2008/11/defense-r...: The discoverers commemorates four European explorers who passed through the Chicago area in the late 1600's. Louis Joliet and Father Jacques Marquette were the first non-native people known to explore the map of Mississippi River system. The traveled down the Chicago River in 1674 on their return to the Great Lakes from the Mississippi Rene Robert Cavelier, Sieur De LaSalle and Henri De Tonti explored the entire Mississippi River basin between 1679 and 1682. Below the sculptural bas relief is inscribed ... "The Discoverers - Jolliet, Father Marquette, La Salle, and Tonti will live in American history as fearless explorers who made their way through the Great Lakes and across this watershed to the Mississippi in the late seventeenth century and typify the spirit of brave adventure which has always been firmly planted in the character of the middle west. Presented to the city by William Wrigley Jr., 1928." . . . . The sculpture is also a favorite place of mine to leave public artwork. ----------- Hi-res print available at www.deviantart.com/print/20378994/

photo.title: Colorful chalk drawing on metal lamp public art graffiti

description._content: The children of Lincoln Square in Chicago took the sidewalk to the Lombard Lamp. I was already lateish to work, but I couldn't pass this up. I setup tripod to capture this HDR. Normally I shoot at f22 to make everything super sharp, but i like this f 1.8 apertture to soften some of the features to help pop the flowers and central fleur de lis. It was challenging making the chalk apparent. The lamp is a nice light blue pumping up the saturation in the photo just blows out the blue of the lamp and doesn't bring out the chalk colors. The split toning in Lightroom helped to tone down the blue of the lamp. I added magenta to the shadows to neutralize the blues of the lamp and bring out the blue chalk. And then I warmed up the temperature overall a bit to bring out the yellow chalk. While I'm not a fan of Ivan Albright, this kinda looks like his paintings in the Art Institute of Chicago. High-resolution print available at www.deviantart.com/print/20090299

photo.title: Have a ball on lion head

description._content: I'm experimenting with the "Have a ball" series by placing single balls in locations. (Previously I would put a handful of bouncy balls in one spot). One of the challenges is how to attach the note to the ball. Tape doesn't really adhere to the ball. A pin is too dangerous for kids. The rubber band works alright. It kinda covers up the ball too much, but that's ok. I kinda like having a collection of bouncy balls together. It encourages people to actually take one of them. In total today I placed bouncy balls in four different locations. I'll be posting the other three soon. This one shown is in Chicago's historic Water Tower. The gallery in Water Tower is a nice small gallery open to the public. One of the permanent features is a lion fountain. The lion likes to play. He also really likes it when you put stuff on his head.
